#Text=Rajkot
#Text=Rajkot
#Text=is a city in the state of Gujarat in Western India .
#Text=Understand
#Text=Rajkot is most famous as the place where Mahatma Gandhi pursued his early education .
#Text=The city is also famous for traditional sweets and dandiya/garba raas dances .
#Text=Founded in 1620 by a member of Jadeja clan , whose descendants ruled the city until 1947 , Rajkot gained economic importance in the early 19th century , under British protectorate .
#Text=Farmers ' and traders ' councils were encouraged to grow under British Rule .
#Text=Later the city plunged into the industrial Age with the first years dominated by casting industries .
#Text=Even today Rajkot is a wealthy city that ranks the 22nd-fastest-growing city in the world .
#Text=It 's also one of the cleanest cities of India .
#Text=Rajkot lies in the middle of Kathiawar peninsula , halfway between Ahmedabad and Porbandar .
#Text=It 's well worth one or two days stop although it 's not a monumental city .
#Text=Rajkot rather appeals to spiritual tastes .
#Text=As in Ahmedabad , many ashrams , that offers the teachings of yoga and meditative retreat , are located in the city and its surroundings , amidst forested hills and beautiful lakes .
#Text=Unfortunately these traditions are not apparent to foreign visitors , especially to those in a hurry .
#Text=Gujarati is the main language .
#Text=Hindi is next most popular .
#Text=A good number of people will have a working knowledge of English too .
#Text=Get in
#Text=Being one of the major cities of Gujarat , Rajkot is well connected to other cities by air and land transport .
#Text=For tourists , it 's usual to either board a flight from Mumbai ( for international arrivals ) to Rajkot .
#Text=For others who are already in India , it 's advisable to reach Ahmadabad ( either by train or by flight ) , and then take a quick bus ride to Rajkot .
#Text=By plane
#Text=Rajkot has a ( RAJ ) which has several flights to Mumbai everyday ( but no flights to Ahmadabad , due to its relative proximity ) , which in turn is well connected with the rest of the world .
#Text=By rail
#Text=is the main railway station .
#Text=There are several direct trains from all parts of India to Rajkot .
#Text=Some of them include longer routes trains from Mumbai , Delhi , Kolkata , Bangalore , Jammu , Kochi , Secunderabad , Thiruvananthapuram , Bhopal etc.
#Text=In common with the rest of India is advisable to book train tickets as early as possible because they are generally not available ( ie , in waiting ) after the booking slot opens .
#Text=Booking tickets 2-3 months prior to the journey is recommended .
#Text=For those who take long distance trains , it is even more advisable .
#Text=By bus
#Text=Rajkot is quite well connected to the entire region of Saurashtra and rest of Gujarat by buses .
#Text=GSRTC Bus Station
#Text=. is located in Karanpara area , just south of the Town Hall .
#Text=If you will be flying out of Ahmedabad , there are some buses that leave from Rajkot and drop you to the Ahmedabad airport .
#Text=They drop you just outside the airport , so be ready to walk about 10 minutes to get to the entrance , but its paved and many people are walking that way .
#Text=A lot of private bus companies have a very well established network around the state with comfortable bus options ( For e.g. Patel Tours and travels , Eagle travels , Neeta travels , etc. . )
#Text=Get around
#Text=As Rajkot lies in the middle of the Saurashtra region , it is very easy to visit many famous places from here , whose relatives distances from Rajkot are small .

#Text=Commuting inside the city can be done via BRTS which covers the roads around the city , but the most favorite is using Auto-richshaws ( best to negotiate the rate of travel before sitting inside ) .
#Text=See
#Text=Watson Museum
#Text=The Watson Museum was established in 1888 and was named after the British Political Agent of Kathiwad , Colonel John Watson .
#Text=The Museum exhibits copies of artifacts from Mohenjodaro , sculptures , costumes of the local tribal people .
#Text=The Lang Library
#Text=, Jawahar Road , Lohana Para ( Near by Watson Museum ) , ☏ +912812224795 , +91 281 2232199 .
#Text=The library has an extensive collection of old books and a repository of reference material linked to the colonial era .
#Text=Mohandas Gandhi High School
#Text=( formerly known as Alfred High School ) , Jawahar Rd , Jubilee Chowk .
#Text=Where Mahatma Gandhi got his primary education .
#Text=The buildings were built by the Nawab of Junagadh and took the name of the Duke Alfred of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha
#Text=Kaba Gandhi No Delo
#Text=, Gheekantha & Dharmendra Rds Crossing .
#Text=Mahatma Gandhi 's childhood residence .
#Text=It has now been converted in to a memorial called " Gandhi Smriti " .
#Text=The museum displays and consists of photographs , objects and the belongings of Mahatma Gandhi .
#Text=Rotary Dolls Museum
#Text=Closed Mondays .
#Text=This unique Museum gives an overview to the culture and traditions of the world at large through a medium of various dolls

#Text=Swaminarayan Temple
#Text=, Kalawad Road , ☏ +912812451000 .
#Text=A temple of BAPS , a socio-spiritual Hindu organization with its roots in the Vedas .
#Text=It was revealed by Bhagwan Swaminarayan ( 1781-1830 ) in the late 18th century and established in 1907 by Shastriji Maharaj ( 1865-1951 ) .
#Text=Shri Ramkrishna Ashram
#Text=, Dr. Yagnik Road , ☏ +91 281-2465200 .
#Text=Has a permanent exhibition showcasing the life of Shri Ramkrishna plus a public library and an Ayurvedic centre

#Text=Panchmukhi Hanuman
#Text=, Garediya Kuva Main Road , ☏ +919924921879 .
#Text=The Temple of Lord Hanuman that is believed to keep the area free of rakshasas ( demons ) .
#Text=A large number of devotees visit the temple every day to get rid of evil spirits .
